Load the dataset

Loading the data doesn't really do anything. It just prepares the df. But we well use the cache() method to keep the data in memory, once it is loaded for the first time.

Load the test data

{% raw %}

df_tst = spark.read.parquet(tst_parquet_folder).cache()
duration = time.time() - start
print("duration: ", duration)

The total number of records in all the quarterly zip files are almost 110'000'000 which is impressive.

Number of different CIKs

The first goal is to find out how many companies deliver reports to the sec. Since every company has a unique cik number, we do this by counting distinct cik.

Test dataset

{% raw %} 
print("{:_}".format(df_tst.select("cik").distinct().count())) # number of unique cik entries in the two test folders

6_147
{% endraw %}

The whole dataset

{% raw %} 
start = time.time()
print("{:_}".format(df_all.select("cik").distinct().count()))
duration = time.time() - start
print("duration: ", duration)

13_068
duration:  42.7621009349823
{% endraw %}

It looks as there are about 13'000 different CIK numbers. It took about 45 seconds, which isn't too bad to scan 110 million entries. That is more than 2 million rows every second.

Number of reports by type

Next we want to see how many different report types (column "form") are filed and how many reports per type are present. In order to do this, we select the columns "adsh" and "form" with distinct, convert the result to a pandas dataframe and use pandas crosstab and seaborn to create the diagram.

{% raw %} 
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd

%matplotlib inline

sns.set()
{% endraw %}

Test dataset

{% raw %} 
p_df_reports_by_type = df_tst.select(["adsh","form"]).distinct().toPandas() # we convert to pandas in order to visualize the data
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
## we use pandas crosstab function to count the entries for each report type
ct = pd.crosstab(index=p_df_reports_by_type['form'], columns='count')
print(ct[:5]) # only print the 5 top entries to get an idea

col_0   count
form         
10-12G      1
10-K      857
10-K/A     88
10-KT       4
10-Q    10719
{% endraw %}

Let us create a nice report with seaborn.

{% raw %} 
my_order = p_df_reports_by_type.groupby(by=['form'])['form'].count().sort_values(ascending=False).index
g = sns.catplot(x='form', kind='count', data=p_df_reports_by_type,  order=my_order, color='skyblue')
g.set_xticklabels(  ## Beschriftung der x-Achse
    rotation=90, ha='center')  ## alias set_horizontalalignment
g.fig.set_figwidth(12)
g.fig.set_figheight(4)
plt.show()
{% endraw %}

The reports we are interested in are the yearly report "10-K" and the quarterly report "10-Q". We would expect that they have a ratio of 1:3 (there should be 3 quarterly and 1 yearly report during the reporting period of one year). But what we see is a ratio of about 1:13. However, our test dataset is from quarter 3 and 4 of 2019. So maybe most companies provide their yearly report in the beginning of the year.

Filer status

There is the field "afs" which defines the "Filer status with the SEC at the time of submission". This field can have the values

  • LAF=Large Accelerated,
  • ACC=Accelerated,
  • SRA=Smaller Reporting Accelerated,
  • NON=Non-Accelerated,
  • SML=Smaller Reporting Filer,
  • NULL=not assigned

It could be interesting to see how they are distributed over the dataset.
Again, the same approach as above is used.
The filer state of a company can change over time, so the number of the selected entries will higher than the number of unique CIKs.

{% raw %} 
start = time.time()
p_df_filer_state = df_all.select(["cik","afs"]).distinct().toPandas() #  convert to pandas in order to visualize the data
duration = time.time() - start
print("duration: ", duration)

duration:  37.35328149795532
{% endraw %} {% raw %} 
print("without filer state: ", p_df_filer_state['afs'].isnull().sum(axis = 0))
print("with filer state   : ", p_df_filer_state['afs'].count())

without filer state:  842
with filer state   :  19782
{% endraw %}

As we can see, 95% of the companies have a filer state.

Primary financial statement

Another interesting field are the entries, which belong to "primary financial statments" (BalanceSheet, CashFlow, IncomeStatement, ..) this are are the one which had a relation to an entry in the pre.txt (the "Presentation") file.

Entries belonging to a "primary financial statement"

{% raw %} 
start = time.time()
print("with filer state   : ", "{:_}".format(df_all.select('stmt').where("stmt is not null").count()))
duration = time.time() - start
print("duration: ", duration)

without filer state   :  67_274_490
duration:  5.7040205001831055
{% endraw %}

It looks as if about two third of the rows in the data belong to a "primary financial statement". That makes sense, since there are is a lot of other information provided in these reports as well.

Lets see how these entries are distributed over the different "primary financial reports". This time, we use the cube function instead of pandas crosstab.

{% raw %} 
start = time.time()
p_df_prim_fin_rep_count = df_all.cube('stmt').count().toPandas()
duration = time.time() - start
print("duration: ", duration)

duration:  20.70000171661377
